\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14}{\ignorespaces Median $f_{\qopname  \relax m{max}}(t)$ per method × noise level (line); IQR band across 30 samples (shaded). Horizontal dotted lines: convergence thresholds $\{0.05, 0.01, 0.005, 0.001\}$. y-axis is log scale. Reading the figure: all GAD curves drop fast for $\sim $50--500 steps then flatten just above $f_{\qopname  \relax m{max}}{=}0.01$. Sella (cyan, train, 100pm only) drops below 0.01 within $\sim $10 steps and continues toward 0.001. GAD's flat region is the ``plateau''; Sella's absence of a flat region is the qualitative difference.\relax }}{24}{figure.caption.52}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {15}{\ignorespaces Same as above but for the mean force norm $\|F\|_{\text  {mean}} = \frac  {1}{N}\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _a \|F_a\|_2$. The qualitative shape mirrors $f_{\qopname  \relax m{max}}$ but at lower absolute values (by definition, mean $\le $ max). The plateau still appears at the same proportional level for GAD ($\sim 0.005$, vs $f_{\qopname  \relax m{max}}\sim 0.01$), confirming the structural-noise-floor hypothesis: it's not a single-atom-mode artifact but a global property of the dynamics near the saddle.\relax }}{25}{figure.caption.53}\protected@file@percent }
